Elastic Net Global Model

From here on out, well only be using the global model and focus specifically on an Elastic Net model; this will better serve our ability to interpret the models.

l = lapply(urge_glmnet$Model, sparse_to_pander)
for(x in 1:length(l)){
  colnames(l[[x]]) = paste("fit", x-1, sep="")
}
do.call(cbind, l)%>%
  pander()

In this fit, many of the parameters yielded similar results, but fit 9 had the most coefficients selected: meanrr, sdann, sdnnix, pnn50, and madrr.

rbind(urge$train, urge$test)%>%
  select(one_of(c("Y", "meanrr")))%>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Y,y=meanrr))+
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill=Y))+
  ggtitle("Mean HRV Before Event vs. Non-Event")+
  scale_fill_discrete(labels = c("Lapse", "Non-Lapse"))+
  theme_minimal()

rbind(urge$train, urge$test)%>%
  select(one_of(c("Y", "sdann")))%>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Y,y=sdann))+
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill=Y))+
  ggtitle("SDANN Before Event vs. Non-Event")+
  scale_fill_discrete(labels = c("Lapse", "Non-Lapse"))+
  theme_minimal()

rbind(urge$train, urge$test)%>%
  select(one_of(c("Y", "sdnnix")))%>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Y,y=sdnnix))+
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill=Y))+
  ggtitle("SDNNIX Before Event vs. Non-Event")+
  scale_fill_discrete(labels = c("Lapse", "Non-Lapse"))+
  theme_minimal()

rbind(urge$train, urge$test)%>%
  select(one_of(c("Y", "pnn50")))%>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Y,y=pnn50))+
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill=Y))+
  ggtitle("PNN50 Before Event vs. Non-Event")+
  scale_fill_discrete(labels = c("Lapse", "Non-Lapse"))+
  theme_minimal()

rbind(urge$train, urge$test)%>%
  select(one_of(c("Y", "madrr")))%>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Y,y=madrr))+
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill=Y), outlier.shape = NA )+
  ggtitle("Median RR Before Event vs. Non-Event\n(Outliers Removed)")+
  scale_fill_discrete(labels = c("Lapse", "Non-Lapse"))+
  theme_minimal()+
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(-0.001,0.002))
